To generate nested objects for documentation purposes, you can use a recursive function that takes in a nested object structure and returns the object in a nested format. Here's an example implementation:

```javascript
const generateNestedObjectsForDocs = (obj, indent = 0) => {
  let result = '';

  // Helper function to add indentation spaces
  const addIndentation = (count) => ' '.repeat(count);

  // Iterate over the keys in the object
  Object.keys(obj).forEach((key) => {
    const value = obj[key];

    // Add the key with appropriate indentation
    result += `${addIndentation(indent)}"${key}": `;

    // Check if the value is an object
    if (typeof value === 'object' && value !== null) {
      // If it is an object, recursively call the function with incremented indentation
      result += `{\n${generateNestedObjectsForDocs(value, indent + 2)}${addIndentation(indent)}}`;
    } else {
      // If it is not an object, add the value as is
      result += `${JSON.stringify(value)}`;
    }

    // Add a comma at the end of each key-value pair except for the last one
    if (key !== Object.keys(obj)[Object.keys(obj).length - 1]) {
      result += ',';
    }

    // Add a new line
    result += '\n';
  });

  return result;
};
```

You can then use this function to generate the nested objects for documentation like this:

```javascript
const nestedObj = {
  key1: 'value1',
  key2: {
    nestedKey1: 'value2',
    nestedKey2: {
      nestedNestedKey: 'value3',
    },
  },
  key3: 'value4',
};

const docString = generateNestedObjectsForDocs(nestedObj);
console.log(docString);
```

